Date: 0/0/1898
Source: Austral English
Author: MORRIS
Vol / Page: 420
Edition:
Quote: <i> slab n.</i> coarse axe-hewn plank, used for rough dwellings called slab-huts. <i> slab v.</i> to reinforce sides of a shaft with timber slabs.<i> slab n. </i> a horse in poor condition. <i> Slab, n.</i> In English, the word <i> slab </i>, as applied to timber, means `an outside piece taken from a log in sawing it into boards, planks, etc.' (`Webster.') In Australia, the word is very common, and denotes a piece of timber, two or three inches thick: a coarse plank, axe-hewn, not sawn. Used for the walls of rough houses.
Notes:

